# Frontend Styling Conventions

This guide defines styling conventions and best practices for the React frontend application using Shadcn UI, Tailwind CSS, and Radix UI.

## CSS Modules (Preferred)

Use CSS Modules for component-specific styles to avoid style conflicts.

### File Naming

- Use `.module.css` extension for CSS Modules
- Match the component file name

```typescript
// ✅ Good
// UserCard.tsx
// UserCard.module.css

// ❌ Bad
// UserCard.tsx
// userCard.css (should be .module.css)
// styles.css (not component-specific)
```

### Usage

```typescript
// ✅ Good - CSS Modules
// UserCard.tsx
import styles from './UserCard.module.css';

export const UserCard = ({ user }: UserCardProps) => {
  return (
    <div className={styles.card}>
      <h3 className={styles.title}>{user.name}</h3>
      <p className={styles.email}>{user.email}</p>
    </div>
  );
};

// UserCard.module.css
.card {
  padding: 1rem;
  border: 1px solid #e0e0e0;
  border-radius: 8px;
}

.title {
  font-size: 1.25rem;
  font-weight: 600;
  margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
}

.email {
  color: #666;
  font-size: 0.875rem;
}
```

## Class Naming Conventions

### BEM-like Naming

Use descriptive, component-scoped class names:

```css
/* ✅ Good - Descriptive class names */
.userCard {
  /* Base component */
}

.userCard__header {
  /* Element */
}

.userCard__header--highlighted {
  /* Modifier */
}

.userCard--active {
  /* Component modifier */
}

/* ❌ Bad - Generic names */
.card {
  /* Too generic */
}

.header {
  /* Not scoped to component */
}
```

## Shadcn UI, Tailwind CSS, and Radix UI

### Core Principles

- **Leverage existing components**: Use the existing components provided by Shadcn UI whenever possible.
- **Customize with Tailwind**: Customize components using styling solutions like Tailwind CSS's utility classes or CSS variables.
- **Create compound components**: Build more complex UI elements by combining existing Shadcn UI components or Radix UI components.
- **Use Shadcn form components**: Use Shadcn UI's form components (e.g., `Input`, `Select`) for handling user input.
- **Implement accessibility**: Implement accessible components by following ARIA guidelines and using appropriate HTML semantics.
- **Use the `cn` utility**: Use the `cn` utility (classnames library) provided by Shadcn UI to manage CSS class names effectively. The `cn` utility is located in `src/utils/utils.ts`. Do not re-create it.
- **Do not modify Shadcn UI components**: Do not directly modify the Shadcn UI component code.
- **Avoid overusing custom CSS**: Do not overuse custom CSS, as Shadcn UI is built with Tailwind CSS.
- **Avoid inline styles**: Refrain from using inline styles as much as possible. Tailwind provides a comprehensive set of utility classes, so most styling needs can be met without resorting to inline styles. Inline styles can make it harder to maintain and update the styles in your project.

### Utility-First Approach with Tailwind

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Tailwind utilities
export const UserCard = ({ user }: UserCardProps) => {
  return (
    <div className="p-4 border border-gray-200 rounded-lg shadow-sm">
      <h3 className="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">{user.name}</h3>
      <p className="text-gray-600 text-sm">{user.email}</p>
    </div>
  );
};
```

### Custom Components with Tailwind

```typescript
// ✅ Good - Extract repeated patterns
// components/ui/Button.tsx
interface ButtonProps {
  variant?: 'primary' | 'secondary' | 'danger';
  children: React.ReactNode;
}

const variantClasses = {
  primary: 'bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700 text-white',
  secondary: 'bg-gray-200 hover:bg-gray-300 text-gray-800',
  danger: 'bg-red-600 hover:bg-red-700 text-white',
};

export const Button = ({ variant = 'primary', children }: ButtonProps) => {
  return (
    <button className={`px-4 py-2 rounded ${variantClasses[variant]}`}>
      {children}
    </button>
  );
};
```

## Responsive Design

### Mobile-First Approach

```css
/* ✅ Good - Mobile-first responsive design */
.userCard {
  padding: 1rem;
  font-size: 0.875rem;
}

@media (min-width: 768px) {
  .userCard {
    padding: 1.5rem;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }
}

@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .userCard {
    padding: 2rem;
  }
}
```

